{"hash":"c165d8b7cae0aeaad97792f783b1c923821f6388","data":{"tag":{"title":"demo","belongsTo":{"edges":[{"node":{"title":"Creating a Rhythm Game With Godot","path":"/creating-a-rhythm-game-with-godot/","date":"3. July 2020","timeToRead":2,"description":"Learn how to use Godot to create a simple rhythm rogue-like game.","cover_image":null,"content":"<h2 id=\"cue-the-track\"><a href=\"#cue-the-track\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>Cue the Track</h2>\n<p>Making a rhythm based game can be a fun new venture if you're looking to make a different type of game and with this tutorial I'll be going over the basis of how to get started with creating your rhythm based game. This tutorial will focus on creating a game similar to <a href=\"\">Crypt of the Necrodancer</a> as it is one of my favorite games of all time and fits right into this category.</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> This demo isn't meant to be used as is, a lot of it is going to be opinionated but the scripts are the core concepts and they can be used other unique ways as you'll see later on.</p>\n<h2 id=\"starting-out\"><a href=\"#starting-out\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>Starting Out</h2>\n<p>To start, create a new Godot project with whatever name you like. Choose a <code>Node2D</code> as the root node and rename it something more suitable like <code>Main</code>. Then save the scene to <code>Main.tscn</code> and finally right click the newly created scene and set it as the main scene. At this point your project should look like:</p>\n<p><img class=\"g-image g-image--lazy g-image--loading\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg fill='none' viewBox='0 0 1921 1020' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' xmlns:xlink='http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink'%3e%3cdefs%3e%3cfilter id='__svg-blur-5c9a94a7371aec47126b5173d00ae383'%3e%3cfeGaussianBlur in='SourceGraphic' stdDeviation='40'/%3e%3c/filter%3e%3c/defs%3e%3cimage x='0' y='0' filter='url(%23__svg-blur-5c9a94a7371aec4